2. Overall Description
2.1 Product Perspective
MobileMechanic is a mobile-first platform with:
•	Frontend: Native iOS and Android apps built with React Native/Flutter for cross-platform compatibility.
•	Backend: RESTful APIs (Django REST Framework or Node.js/Express) handling authentication, bookings, and dispatch logic.
•	External Interfaces:
o	Maps: Google Maps API for location services and mechanic tracking.
o	Payments: Integration with local PSPs (JazzCash, Easypaisa) and potentially Stripe for future scalability.
o	Notifications: SMS (Twilio) and push notifications (Firebase Cloud Messaging).
The system operates as a three-tier architecture: client (mobile apps), server (APIs and database), and external services (maps, payments, notifications).
2.2 User Needs
•	Convenience: Schedule services at home or office with minimal effort.
•	Transparency: View clear pricing, mechanic details, and real-time tracking.
•	Trust: Certified mechanics, secure payments, and user ratings/reviews.
•	Accessibility: Support for Urdu/English languages and intuitive UI.
2.3 Assumptions and Dependencies
•	Assumptions:
o	Users have smartphones with internet access (3G/4G or Wi-Fi).
o	Mechanics are willing to travel to customer locations.
o	Local regulations allow on-site car maintenance in residential/commercial areas.
•	Dependencies:
o	Availability of Google Maps API (or equivalent) for geolocation and tracking.
o	Reliable integration with local PSPs for payments.
o	Access to SMS providers (e.g., Twilio) for OTP and notifications.
3. Functional Requirements
3.1 User Management
•	FR-1: Users can sign up/login using phone number with OTP or email/password.
•	FR-2: Users can create/edit profiles, including vehicle details (make, model, year, last service date).
•	FR-3: Password reset via OTP sent to registered phone/email.
3.2 Service Booking Workflow
•	FR-4: Display a categorized list of services (e.g., oil change, tyre repair) with descriptions and estimated prices.
•	FR-5: Allow users to input service location via GPS or manual address entry.
•	FR-6: Enable scheduling with date/time selection and display estimated mechanic arrival time.
•	FR-7: Send booking confirmation via SMS/push notification.
3.3 Real-Time Dispatch and Tracking
•	FR-8: Automatically assign the nearest available mechanic based on location and skills.
•	FR-9: Provide real-time mechanic tracking in a map view (Google Maps or equivalent).
•	FR-10: Offer in-app chat or call functionality between user and mechanic.
3.4 Payments and Receipts
•	FR-11: Support payments via local PSPs (JazzCash, Easypaisa) and cash on delivery.
•	FR-12: Generate digital invoices with breakdown of parts, labor, and taxes.
•	FR-13: Store payment history for user reference.


3.5 Service History and Ratings
•	FR-14: Maintain a record of completed services with details (date, service type, cost, mechanic).
•	FR-15: Allow users to rate mechanics (1–5 stars) and provide optional feedback post-service.
3.6 Mechanic Module
•	FR-16: Mechanics can register with personal details, certifications, and service specialties.
•	FR-17: Mechanics can toggle availability (on/off) and view assigned bookings.
•	FR-18: Provide navigation to job locations via in-app maps.
•	FR-19: Allow mechanics to mark jobs as completed and upload job notes/photos (e.g., for damage assessment).
3.7 Admin Dashboard
•	FR-20: Web-based dashboard to list and manage bookings, users, and mechanics.
•	FR-21: Enable verification of mechanic certifications and dispute resolution.
•	FR-22: Generate analytics reports (e.g., monthly bookings, revenue, top mechanics, popular services).
4. Non-Functional Requirements
4.1 Performance
•	NFR-1: Booking confirmation response time ≤ 2 seconds under normal conditions.
•	NFR-2: Map loading and tracking updates ≤ 3 seconds on 3G networks.
•	NFR-3: API response time for critical operations (e.g., booking, payment) ≤ 500ms.
4.2 Scalability
•	NFR-4: Support 10,000 simultaneous users across multiple cities (e.g., Lahore, Karachi, Islamabad).
•	NFR-5: Backend should handle peak loads (e.g., 1,000 bookings/hour) without degradation.
4.3 Security
•	NFR-6: Use HTTPS/TLS 1.2+ for all API communications.
•	NFR-7: Encrypt sensitive user data (e.g., phone, payment details) per Pakistan’s data protection laws.
•	NFR-8: Implement role-based access control (RBAC) for User, Mechanic, and Admin roles.
4.4 Reliability and Availability
•	NFR-9: System uptime ≥ 99.5% (excluding scheduled maintenance).
•	NFR-10: Auto-retry for failed SMS/push notifications or payment transactions (up to 3 retries).
4.5 Usability
•	NFR-11: Intuitive UI with ≤ 3 steps to complete a booking.
•	NFR-12: Support Urdu and English languages with RTL support for Urdu.
•	NFR-13: Accessible design (e.g., high-contrast UI, readable fonts) per WCAG 2.1 guidelines.
4.6 Maintainability
•	NFR-14: Modular codebase with clear separation of concerns (e.g., MVC or microservices).
•	NFR-15: Comprehensive documentation for API endpoints, database schema, and app workflows.
•	NFR-16: Automated unit tests covering ≥ 80% of backend code.
5. External Interface Requirements
5.1 APIs
•	Google Maps API: For geolocation, routing, and real-time tracking.
•	Twilio API: For SMS-based OTP and notifications.
•	JazzCash/Easypaisa APIs: For secure payment processing.
•	Firebase Cloud Messaging: For push notifications.
5.2 Hardware Interfaces
•	GPS: Required for user location input and mechanic tracking.
•	Camera: Optional for mechanics to upload job-related photos (e.g., damage assessment).
•	Network: 3G/4G or Wi-Fi for app functionality.
